What is the story of Zaharia, 82, a tale that cannot find justice in mere fleeting images? A generation born before and around World War Two, they have endured unyielding toughness throughout their lives, carrying it with them until the very end. Wars, famines, communism‚Äîthese trials have left just a handful of them behind. But as a nation, have we failed to protect them and provide the closure they deserve? In the villages where the young have departed to seek work in bustling cities or foreign lands, a poignant silence now lingers. Once vibrant communities, these villages embody a fading way of life. The simplicity of days spent tending to fields, the joyous gatherings celebrating harvests, and the warm hearths that nurtured tight-knit families have all waned with time. Now, the elders remain, reminiscing about a past that seems distant and unreal to the younger generations who have chosen different paths. The old ways, deeply rooted in tradition and close-knit bonds, now struggle to survive in the face of modernity's relentless advance. The resilience of these villagers stands as a testament to their enduring spirit, forged through enduring the darkest days of history. Yet, as they bear witness to the departure of their youth, a question lingers: Will the stories of their struggles and the beauty of their traditions find a place in the hearts of those who have moved on? Don't forget that Florida has many natural springs to explore! These two springs are located about 1hr away from Panama City Beach or Destin. Ponce De Leon Springs- it's $4 per vehicle to get into the park and It's open from 8am until sunset all year. The spring water is 68 degrees Fahrenheit all year round so it is chilly! I saw people bring tubes with umbrellas to float around here and thought that was such a good idea! There are nature trails you can walk around as well. Morrison Springs County Park- this spot is near Ponce De Leon and has more of a natural feel to it. It's a popular spot for diving and even has a small cave divers can go into! This is a great spot to kayak too. It includes a diving dock, boat ramp, and boardwalks. It's free to visit! This was my favorite thing we did on our last Florida trip!
